This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

Fixes https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/83111.

When `#!` appeared at column 0 of a non-first line, the compiler reported CS1040 ("Preprocessor directives must appear as the first non-whitespace character on a line"), which is incorrect — the shebang *is* the first character on that line. The real problem is that it's not on line 1.

## Changes

- **New error CS9378 (`ERR_PPShebangNotOnFirstLine`)**: `'#!' must be the first characters on the first line of the file`
- **`DirectiveParser.cs`**: CS9378 is now unconditionally reported for *any* invalid `#!` placement — whether it appears on a non-first line, has leading whitespace, or has whitespace between `#` and `!`. CS1040 is no longer used for shebang directives.
- **`ErrorCode.cs` / `CSharpResources.resx` / `ErrorFacts.cs`**: Register the new error code.

### Before / After

```csharp
// Input (with FileBasedProgram feature)
class Foo { }
#!/usr/bin/env dotnet

// Before: (2,1): error CS1040: Preprocessor directives must appear as the first non-whitespace character on a line
// After:  (2,1): error CS9378: '#!' must be the first characters on the first line of the file
```

CS9378 also now fires for previously CS1040 cases like ` #!xyz` (whitespace before `#!` on the same line).

I've been working on a [set of analyzers](https://github.com/dotnet-project-file-analyzers/dotnet-project-file-analyzers) to suggest improvements on (MSBuild) files, using Roslyn. For on of these rules ([Only use UTF8 without BOM](https://github.com/dotnet-project-file-analyzers/dotnet-project-file-analyzers/blob/main/src/DotNetProjectFile.Analyzers/Analyzers/Generic/OnlyUseUTF8WithoutBom.cs)) I've tried to implement a `CodeFixProvider`:

``` C#
public sealed class RemoveBomHeader : CodeFixProvider
{
    public sealed override ImmutableArray<string> FixableDiagnosticIds => ["Proj3000"];

    public override Task RegisterCodeFixesAsync(CodeFixContext context)
    {
        if (context.Diagnostics.FirstOrDefault() is { } diagnostic)
        {
            context.RegisterCodeFix(
                CodeAction.Create(
                    "Remove UTF-8 BOM header",
                    _ => UpdateDocument(context.Document),
                    "Proj3000.Fix"),
                diagnostic);
        }

        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    private static async Task<Document> UpdateDocument(Document document)
    {
        using var stream = new FileInfo(document.FilePath).OpenRead();
        if (stream is { Length: > 3, CanRead: true, CanSeek: true })
        {
            stream.Position = 3;
            return document.WithText(SourceText.From(stream));
        }
        else return document;
    }

    /// <inheritdoc />
    public sealed override FixAllProvider? GetFixAllProvider() => WellKnownFixAllProviders.BatchFixer;
}
```

Although all files (code, csproj, slnx, and others) are reported on correctly, and when opened in Visual Studio I get visual indications when a certain file contains a BOM. However, the code fix does not show up.

Am I doing something wrong? Or is it due to the fact that those 3 byte are not displayed?

